<DocLayout
  title="Getting Started"
  description="How to download Emu198x releases, build from source when needed, and understand where screenshots, ROMs, media, scripts, and MCP fit."
>
  <h1>Getting started</h1>

  <p>
    Emu198x ships per-system binaries through GitHub Releases. Download the
    archive for the machine and platform you want, or build the same per-system
    binary from source when developing locally. There is no planned unified CLI
    launcher; choose the machine you want to run.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the emulator project. <a href="https://code198x.com">Code Like It's
    198x</a> is the separate teaching site in the wider 198x family. It may use
    emulator screenshots or workflows, but this documentation is about running
    and inspecting Emu198x itself.
  </p>

  <h2>Download a release</h2>

  <p>
    Start at the <a href="/downloads/">downloads page</a>. It links to GitHub
    Releases and lists the primary per-system binaries and desktop platforms.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pick the archive matching both the system and your operating system, unpack
    it, then run the binary directly. The examples below use
    {' '}<code>cargo run</code> because they also work from a source checkout;
    with a release archive, use the unpacked binary name instead:
  </p>

  <pre><code># Source checkout form
cargo run --release -p emu198x-nes --no-default-features -- \
  --rom game.nes \
  --frames 300 \
  --screenshot nes.png

# Release archive form
./emu198x-nes --rom game.nes --frames 300 --screenshot nes.png</code></pre>

  <h2>What can I run today?</h2>

  <p>
    Start with one of the primary systems if you want the most complete
    experience: ZX Spectrum, Commodore 64, Nintendo NES, Commodore Amiga,
    Nintendo Game Boy, or Dragon 32. Those are the best places to try windowed
    use, screenshots, scripted runs, and MCP-driven inspection.
  </p>

  <p>
    Extended systems are useful for boot captures, scripting, and MCP work, but
    many are still headless and some need local firmware or cartridge media.
    The <a href="/systems/">system matrix</a> shows the current screenshot
    evidence, and the <a href="/docs/status/current-system-usability/">usability
    matrix</a> gives the deeper status notes.
  </p>

  <h2>Build from source</h2>

  <p>
    Source builds are useful for development, checking unreleased changes, or
    working with systems outside the primary release set. Install a current
    stable Rust toolchain, clone the emulator repository, and build the specific
    binary you want:
  </p>

  <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/emu198x/emu198x.git
cd emu198x
cargo build --release -p emu198x-spectrum</code></pre>

  <p>
    During development, <code>cargo run --release -p PACKAGE -- ...</code> is
    usually the simplest form. Use <code>--help</code> on a package before
    assuming flags transfer exactly between systems.
  </p>

  <h2>ROMs and media</h2>

  <p>
    Emu198x does not ship commercial ROMs, firmware, disks, tapes, or
    cartridges. You provide those yourself from hardware you own or another
    legal source. The requirements differ by machine:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>NES and Game Boy cartridge runs use the cartridge image you provide.</li>
    <li>Commodore 64, Amiga, Dragon, MSX, and many extended systems need local firmware or ROM paths.</li>
    <li>Screenshots and software smokes that depend on commercial media stay gated behind local paths.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>First screenshot</h2>

  <p>
    A headless screenshot is the quickest smoke test because it does not require
    the native window feature. For example, with an NES cartridge image:
  </p>

  <pre><code>cargo run --release -p emu198x-nes --no-default-features -- \
  --rom game.nes \
  --frames 300 \
  --screenshot nes.png</code></pre>

  <p>
    For a firmware-based machine, pass the local ROM or firmware directory the
    runner expects. A C64 disk autoload run looks like this:
  </p>

  <pre><code>cargo run --release -p emu198x-c64 -- \
  --rom-dir ~/.emu198x/roms/commodore-c64 \
  --disk game.d64 \
  --autoload-disk</code></pre>

  <h2>First windowed run</h2>

  <p>
    Primary systems with native windows can run without
    {' '}<code>--no-default-features</code>. Cartridge-first machines are the easiest
    examples:
  </p>

  <pre><code>cargo run --release -p emu198x-nes -- game.nes</code></pre>

  <pre><code>cargo run --release -p emu198x-game-boy -- game.gb</code></pre>

  <p>
    For Amiga and C64, expect to point the runner at the right firmware and
    media. For Spectrum tape work, use the ROM and tape/autoload flags:
  </p>

  <pre><code>cargo run --release -p emu198x-spectrum -- \
  --rom 48.rom \
  --tape game.tzx \
  --autoload-tape</code></pre>

  <h2>Where scripting and MCP fit</h2>

  <p>
    Scripts are for repeatable local automation: run frames, load media, press
    keys, query state, and save screenshots or audio. MCP is the agent-facing
    surface over the same kind of control and inspection model.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use <a href="/docs/features/scripting/">scripting</a> when you want a file
    you can run in CI or reuse locally. Use <a href="/docs/features/mcp/">MCP</a>{' '}
    when an external tool or agent should drive the emulator over stdio. For
    example:
  </p>

  <pre><code>cargo run --release -p emu198x-atari-800xl -- --mcp</code></pre>

